00:02:24.146 --> 00:02:27.206 A:middle
Let's talk about
the fundamentals.

00:02:28.136 --> 00:02:31.086 A:middle
Now when Xcode builds
and signs your app,

00:02:31.426 --> 00:02:34.866 A:middle
behind the scenes it uses
a tool called codesign.

00:02:35.886 --> 00:02:38.776 A:middle
Now if you're new, you don't
need to think about this.

00:02:39.176 --> 00:02:41.416 A:middle
Xcode does this for
you automatically.

00:02:41.936 --> 00:02:44.536 A:middle
And if you're experienced, you
might be wondering, signing.

00:02:44.876 --> 00:02:45.786 A:middle
How does it work?

00:02:45.966 --> 00:02:47.906 A:middle
Well, we use this codesign tool.

00:02:48.356 --> 00:02:51.766 A:middle
And what codesign does is,
it takes your app's bundle

00:02:51.956 --> 00:02:53.786 A:middle
and applies a code seal.

00:02:54.566 --> 00:02:57.336 A:middle
And this allows the
system to detect changes

00:02:57.336 --> 00:03:00.466 A:middle
that have been made after
the app has been signed.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:57.336 --> 00:03:00.466 A:middle
that have been made after
the app has been signed.

00:03:01.676 --> 00:03:06.046 A:middle
So if someone messes with your
app, it won't install or launch.

00:03:07.296 --> 00:03:12.026 A:middle
Codesign also applies a code
signature to the application.

00:03:12.336 --> 00:03:13.976 A:middle
So it can be identified.

00:03:14.146 --> 00:03:17.066 A:middle
And people know where
the app came from.

00:03:20.136 --> 00:03:24.096 A:middle
There are three things that you
need in order to sign your apps.

00:03:24.886 --> 00:03:27.386 A:middle
The first thing is a
signing certificate.

00:03:27.716 --> 00:03:31.786 A:middle
Signing certificates establish
your identity as a developer.

00:03:33.156 --> 00:03:36.376 A:middle
Provisioning profiles
are all about your apps,

00:03:36.556 --> 00:03:37.846 A:middle
and they grant permissions.

00:03:38.466 --> 00:03:43.136 A:middle
And entitlements declare
support for capabilities.

00:03:43.336 --> 00:03:44.876 A:middle
Like iCloud or Wallet.

00:03:46.676 --> 00:03:48.006 A:middle
So certificates.

00:03:48.526 --> 00:03:50.206 A:middle
These are issued by Apple.

00:03:50.556 --> 00:03:53.946 A:middle
And this is important because
the device needs a trust chain

00:03:53.946 --> 00:03:57.206 A:middle
back to Apple so it
can install the app.

00:03:58.016 --> 00:04:00.526 A:middle
And certificates
come in two forms.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:58.016 --> 00:04:00.526 A:middle
And certificates
come in two forms.

00:04:00.916 --> 00:04:02.666 A:middle
You have development
certificates,

00:04:03.396 --> 00:04:04.626 A:middle
which are for build and run.

00:04:05.026 --> 00:04:07.216 A:middle
And you have distribution
certificates.

00:04:07.586 --> 00:04:08.466 A:middle
Which are used

00:04:08.566 --> 00:04:10.716 A:middle
for authentication
with iTunes Connect.

00:04:11.296 --> 00:04:14.296 A:middle
Or, if these are
enterprise certificates,

00:04:14.466 --> 00:04:16.435 A:middle
it's for distribution to users.

00:04:18.296 --> 00:04:22.466 A:middle
And all signing certificates
require a private key.

00:04:22.906 --> 00:04:25.556 A:middle
This private key has
to be in the keychain

00:04:25.716 --> 00:04:28.026 A:middle
if you want to sign your apps.

00:04:28.206 --> 00:04:31.446 A:middle
And the private key for
a certificate is created

00:04:31.446 --> 00:04:33.276 A:middle
when the certificate
gets generated.

00:04:33.276 --> 00:04:36.206 A:middle
And so it's very important
to have this private key.

00:04:37.486 --> 00:04:38.836 A:middle
And it's worth noting here

00:04:38.836 --> 00:04:42.056 A:middle
that Apple never has a
copy of your private keys.

00:04:42.196 --> 00:04:45.036 A:middle
You can't go to the developer
website and download them.

00:04:45.536 --> 00:04:49.216 A:middle
Now the good news
is, in Xcode 8,

00:04:49.396 --> 00:04:51.836 A:middle
for your development
certificates, you don't need

00:04:51.836 --> 00:04:53.066 A:middle
to worry about this anymore.

00:04:53.186 --> 00:04:57.106 A:middle
And we'll talk more
about that in a second.

00:04:57.226 --> 00:05:00.176 A:middle
Provisioning profiles
are also issued by Apple.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:57.226 --> 00:05:00.176 A:middle
Provisioning profiles
are also issued by Apple.

00:05:00.666 --> 00:05:03.646 A:middle
And in contrast to
certificates which are all

00:05:03.646 --> 00:05:05.616 A:middle
about your identity
as a developer,

00:05:06.056 --> 00:05:08.826 A:middle
the profiles are
all about your apps.

00:05:10.956 --> 00:05:14.856 A:middle
Profiles allow access to
things like running on devices.

00:05:15.356 --> 00:05:18.396 A:middle
There's a list of
identifiers in a profile.

00:05:18.526 --> 00:05:22.156 A:middle
And at install time, the
device runs down those list

00:05:22.156 --> 00:05:24.936 A:middle
of identifiers to check
if yours is included.

00:05:25.176 --> 00:05:28.006 A:middle
And if it is, you
can install the app.

00:05:28.896 --> 00:05:33.066 A:middle
Profiles also allow
access to entitlements.

00:05:33.506 --> 00:05:36.406 A:middle
There's a white list of
entitlements in a profile.

00:05:36.786 --> 00:05:38.436 A:middle
And if you want to
use an entitlement,

00:05:38.606 --> 00:05:40.416 A:middle
it has to be in that list.

00:05:41.436 --> 00:05:43.116 A:middle
Now once again, if you're new,

00:05:43.276 --> 00:05:44.666 A:middle
you don't need to
think about this.

00:05:44.666 --> 00:05:46.296 A:middle
Xcode handles this for you.

00:05:46.646 --> 00:05:48.196 A:middle
And if you're experienced,

00:05:48.396 --> 00:05:51.366 A:middle
you might be wondering
why you need a new profile

00:05:51.516 --> 00:05:54.246 A:middle
when you add an entitlement
to your app.

00:05:54.406 --> 00:05:57.186 A:middle
It's because of that white list.

00:05:57.816 --> 00:05:59.256 A:middle
Speaking of entitlements,

00:05:59.936 --> 00:06:02.766 A:middle
entitlements declare
support for capabilities.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:59.936 --> 00:06:02.766 A:middle
entitlements declare
support for capabilities.

00:06:03.566 --> 00:06:06.826 A:middle
And fundamentally an
entitlement is just a string

00:06:07.326 --> 00:06:08.826 A:middle
with an associated value.

00:06:08.996 --> 00:06:10.206 A:middle
Like a string or a bowl.

00:06:10.736 --> 00:06:13.736 A:middle
And these are defined
per target.

00:06:14.186 --> 00:06:16.886 A:middle
So if your app uses one
set of capabilities,

00:06:17.286 --> 00:06:20.416 A:middle
and your app extension uses
another set, that's fine.

00:06:20.896 --> 00:06:25.966 A:middle
And Xcode has a dedicated editor
for working with capabilities,

00:06:26.336 --> 00:06:27.716 A:middle
called the Capabilities tab.

00:06:28.316 --> 00:06:32.366 A:middle
And the Capabilities tab will
manage your entitlements PLIST

00:06:32.596 --> 00:06:34.186 A:middle
in the configuration details.

00:06:34.566 --> 00:06:36.976 A:middle
So you don't have to visit
the developer website.

00:06:37.206 --> 00:06:39.336 A:middle
You can do it all
from within Xcode.

00:06:39.876 --> 00:06:44.576 A:middle
So those are the things you
need in order to sign your apps.

00:06:45.026 --> 00:06:48.066 A:middle
Now what happens when Xcode
goes to sign your app?

00:06:48.366 --> 00:06:50.326 A:middle
It needs to know which
certificate to use,

00:06:50.326 --> 00:06:51.586 A:middle
and which provision and profile.

00:06:52.106 --> 00:06:55.616 A:middle
The way that works is,
Xcode will build your app.

00:06:56.276 --> 00:07:00.066 A:middle
And then it looks at the list
of certificates on your machine.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:56.276 --> 00:07:00.066 A:middle
And then it looks at the list
of certificates on your machine.

00:07:00.376 --> 00:07:04.286 A:middle
And it picks the newest one that
matches your development team.

00:07:05.236 --> 00:07:07.866 A:middle
Xcode then looks at
the list of profiles.

00:07:08.356 --> 00:07:11.326 A:middle
And it picks the newest one
that matches your bundle ID.

00:07:11.326 --> 00:07:14.056 A:middle
And these two things
are brought together.

00:07:14.446 --> 00:07:16.776 A:middle
The profile is embedded
in the app.

00:07:17.736 --> 00:07:19.856 A:middle
And the certificate
is used with Code Sign

00:07:20.076 --> 00:07:21.206 A:middle
to apply the code seal.

00:07:21.736 --> 00:07:25.266 A:middle
So that's a quick
run through of some

00:07:25.266 --> 00:07:28.286 A:middle
of the fundamentals
of signing your apps.

00:07:29.346 --> 00:07:32.866 A:middle
Let's talk now about the
changes we've made for setting

00:07:32.866 --> 00:07:35.166 A:middle
up new machines with
signing certificates.

00:07:36.536 --> 00:07:38.926 A:middle
So who's seen this before?

00:07:39.716 --> 00:07:42.956 A:middle
Yeah. Your account
already has a certificate,

00:07:43.096 --> 00:07:45.016 A:middle
and Xcode offers to reset it.

00:07:45.536 --> 00:07:49.096 A:middle
So what happens when
you click that button?

00:07:49.246 --> 00:07:50.816 A:middle
Yeah, so what happens
is it gets rid

00:07:50.816 --> 00:07:52.706 A:middle
of your current cert
and makes a new one.

00:07:53.586 --> 00:07:54.636 A:middle
And why is this?

00:07:55.046 --> 00:07:57.616 A:middle
Well, your development
account has a limit

00:07:57.616 --> 00:07:59.436 A:middle
of one signing certificate.

00:07:59.916 --> 00:08:03.646 A:middle
And if you have a single
machine, this works great.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:59.916 --> 00:08:03.646 A:middle
And if you have a single
machine, this works great.

00:08:04.036 --> 00:08:05.156 A:middle
The cert is created.

00:08:05.156 --> 00:08:08.356 A:middle
You have a private key that's
generated, and it stays

00:08:08.356 --> 00:08:10.296 A:middle
in your keychain
and it just works.

00:08:11.236 --> 00:08:14.556 A:middle
Now what happens if
you have a second Mac?

00:08:15.056 --> 00:08:17.926 A:middle
Well, to build and sign
on that second Mac,

00:08:18.426 --> 00:08:20.896 A:middle
you need a signing
cert and a private key.

00:08:21.346 --> 00:08:26.206 A:middle
And you can either sync that
over using keychain access

00:08:26.206 --> 00:08:29.386 A:middle
or Xcode and import the
private key on the second Mac.

00:08:30.226 --> 00:08:32.796 A:middle
Or you can create a new
signing certificate.

00:08:33.246 --> 00:08:35.905 A:middle
But that first requires
getting rid of the old one.

00:08:36.635 --> 00:08:39.816 A:middle
And now you can build on the
second Mac, but you can't build

00:08:39.816 --> 00:08:41.035 A:middle
on your first Mac anymore.

00:08:41.635 --> 00:08:44.836 A:middle
And it's easy to repeat this
process, and go back and forth

00:08:44.836 --> 00:08:47.946 A:middle
between being able to build on
one machine, and not being able

00:08:47.946 --> 00:08:49.116 A:middle
to build on another one.

00:08:49.116 --> 00:08:51.956 A:middle
And this is really
frustrating and cumbersome.

00:08:52.856 --> 00:08:55.536 A:middle
Well, the good news
is in Xcode 8,

00:08:55.536 --> 00:08:58.636 A:middle
you can now have multiple
development certificates.

00:08:59.316 --> 00:09:00.146 A:middle
So -- yeah [applause].


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:59.316 --> 00:09:00.146 A:middle
So -- yeah [applause].

00:09:03.806 --> 00:09:07.206 A:middle
Each of your machines can have
their own dedicated certificate

00:09:07.406 --> 00:09:08.396 A:middle
and private key.

00:09:08.616 --> 00:09:11.566 A:middle
So you never have to sync
private keys for development,

00:09:12.316 --> 00:09:13.966 A:middle
and you don't have
to see this again.

00:09:16.136 --> 00:09:20.026 A:middle
These changes apply just for
development certificates.

00:09:20.476 --> 00:09:23.336 A:middle
Your distribution certs
still have a limit of one

00:09:23.336 --> 00:09:24.436 A:middle
that you need to manage.

00:09:26.216 --> 00:09:30.286 A:middle
These are created both through
Xcode or the developer websites.

00:09:30.686 --> 00:09:34.476 A:middle
And these are created
in Xcode 8 and later.

00:09:36.186 --> 00:09:39.526 A:middle
And if you have an old copy
of Xcode on your machine,

00:09:39.976 --> 00:09:43.156 A:middle
and you create one of these new
signing certificates, it works.

00:09:43.216 --> 00:09:45.466 A:middle
They're 100% backwards
compatible.

00:09:46.026 --> 00:09:50.436 A:middle
So that's what we've changed

00:09:50.666 --> 00:09:53.226 A:middle
about signing certificates
in Xcode 8.

00:09:54.436 --> 00:09:56.966 A:middle
I'd like to turn the stage
over to my colleague, Itai,

00:09:56.966 --> 00:09:59.136 A:middle
who's going to tell you
about the new workflows

00:09:59.686 --> 00:10:02.296 A:middle
in Xcode 8 [applause].


WEBVTT
